status_message: "Hepatitis B annually kills more than 500,000 people worldwide. Although it is preventable by vaccine, more than 240 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B. status_message:
Indiana University is aware of the public attention over the court's adjudication involving John Enochs, who is no longer a student at the university nor a graduate of IU, and has received a number of inquiries requesting comment on the case.  
 
As result of the Federal Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA), designed to protect the educational records of students, Indiana University is not able to publicly comment on individual student misconduct cases, including the final disposition of those cases. Additionally, it would be inappropriate for the university to comment on the outcome of a criminal judicial proceeding to which it is not a party.
 
As it relates to sexual misconduct, however, the university continues to utilize robust processes that are designed to support victims, while at the same time affording due process to those accused of misconduct. In instances where a student is found responsible for committing an act of sexual violence, the penalty is suspension or expulsion.
 
Additionally, the university regularly engages in a broad range of educational communication and programming to students, faculty and staff regarding sexual assault. The university's goals are both to prevent sexual assault whenever possible and to support the victims to the fullest extent possible. 
 
For more information on the university's programs and policies related to sexual misconduct go to www.stopsexualviolence.iu.edu

"My fondest memory from IU is IUDM 2015, the fourth and final IU Dance Marathon event that I participated in as an undergrad. The 36-hour event that took place last October was a culmination of every ounce of passion, dedication, and heart that all 4,000 student members had put into fundraising for Riley Hospital throughout the year. At the end of the event we raised a total of $3.88 million dollars benefitting the children at Riley Hospital. Seeing that total and knowing that that was the conclusion of my time as a student leader with IUDM, was the most fulfilling and rewarding experience I've ever had.

As a lifelong Hoosier fan, Indiana University has had a significant impact on me since childhood. Despite knowing how special of a place this is, I still never could have imagined graduating from IU with the level of experience, purpose, or passion that this university has provided me."

- Michelle Turchan, a 2016 graduate of Indiana University School of Public and Environmental Affairs (SPEA)

A Legacy of Strength.

"Far too many communities around the world are still having trouble accessing clean water, which has become the world's largest health crisis. That's why, in 2013, I decided to work with a group of students to help establish an IU chapter for the Timmy Water Project. Since we founded this program, we have been able to provide millions of gallons of clean water for over 400 families in Ecuador. During summer break this year, we will be travelling to the Dominican Republic to continue our mission of providing safe water solutions to impoverished communities." ‚Äì Kenneth Guerra, senior in IU's College of Arts and Sciences #HoosiersofIU

A culture of perpetual discovery.

"Before I graduate with a tourism, hospitality, and event management degree, I decided to intern at an eco-friendly diving company on the North Shore of Oahu, Hawaii. Around 25% of all of the fish and underwater plant life near Hawaii is endemic, meaning that it only exists here. During each dive, I not only ensure diver safety, but I also educate divers on the importance of protecting the rare species around them. It's crazy to think that by the end of my internship I'll be a certified dive master and an alumnus of Indiana University." ‚Äì Colt Kitchin, senior in IU's School of Public Health #HoosiersofIU

"During my time at IU, I have had the pleasure of attending IU's annual Unity Summit that happens on Martin Luther King Jr. Day. status_message: "When it comes to learning about a specific culture, dancing is one of the easiest ways to do that. I decided to team up with La Casa (IU's Latino Cultural Center) to create Paso A Paso, a free program that educates the community on Latino culture through dance. Paso A Paso means step-by-step. In the aftermath of Friday's tragic attacks in Paris, Indiana University immediately began reaching out to individual students and programs in France where IU students are studying  to ensure they were safe and to provide any necessary support. The university is happy to be able to report that all 17 IU students studying in France this semester (15 IU Bloomington students and two IUPUI students) are safe. In addition, we have received word that other students currently studying in Europe this semester, and who may have been traveling in France yesterday,  are also safe.

The safety of our students while traveling abroad is of the utmost importance to the university. At this time, the university is not recommending that students return to the United States, but we will continue to closely monitor events in Paris and around the world to provide as much support as possible to our students who are studying abroad.

In addition, our thoughts and best wishes go out to our students from France currently studying at IU. The university has reached out to this group and stands ready to provide any support our students may need as they deal with this horrific situation.

An important message to our community from Indiana University Bloomingon Provost Lauren Robel:

The IU Police Department has received reports of a racist threat made through anonymous social media. IU utterly condemns such reprehensible threats. IUPD does not believe that the post represents a credible threat of physical violence. Nonetheless, campus police are on high alert and IU students, faculty, and staff should report any suspicious behavior immediately to the police at 812-855-4111.

We completely reject this cowardly and anonymous action, intended to inject fear and divisiveness into what should be an open and honest set of conversations about the state of inclusiveness in our community.

Lauren Robel, IU Bloomington Provost

status_message:
President Michael McRobbie reaffirmed IU's unwavering commitment to diversity and inclusion while at IU Northwest in Gary this evening:
 
Student success depends upon more than the content of individual courses or the curriculum of particular degree programs.
 
An important part of it is conditioned by an environment that provides support in other ways, from student organizations that encourage personal and social growth; to services that support the physical and mental health and wellness of students; to physical environments that are safe and inspiring; and to building a community in which diversity of community and ideas is valued and in which all members of the community are committed to the highest standards of ethical conduct and integrity.
 
Indiana University's longstanding commitment to embracing diversity in the broadest sense is also fundamental to student success.
 
The Bicentennial Strategic Plan embodies that commitment as a core value, and, in light of recent events at other universities that have made national headlines, let me take a moment this evening to underscore and reaffirm Indiana University's unwavering commitment to diversity and free expression.
 
As part that commitment, we recruit students and faculty from diverse cultural backgrounds.
 
We strive to ensure that cultural diversity is well represented in the curriculum.
 
And we seek to ensure that members of our community who come from diverse backgrounds interact with one another in educationally purposeful ways.

For through continued interaction with others who hold views that differ from our own‚Äîwhose life experiences are vastly different from ours‚Äîour minds are opened to new ways of understanding.
 
We comprehend, we empathize, we learn.
 
We must, all of us, bend our efforts‚Äîevery day, and not just in the wake of a particular incident‚Äîto assure that our university community regards tolerance and tolerant diversity and the free expression of ideas as among its core values.
 
The Bicentennial Campaign will help us to continue to broaden and strengthen a culture of diversity on all IU campuses.

status_message: "I had an allergic reaction to a vaccination that ended my six-year career with the military. Filing for benefits through the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs was a real nightmare. It was also hard seeing so many other veterans, who are far worse off than I am, struggle with every step of the compensation process. I found a job posting from IU law professor Carwina Weng asking for assistance with a disability law clinic she was hosting through the Maurer School of Law. Soon after accepting the position, I began establishing a veteran's clinic for disabled veterans, the first to be created in a law school in Indiana. Now, we are proudly accepting veterans for our disability assistance program, which allows students to get hands-on experience in the field while helping benefit the veterans in the community. It's extremely gratifying knowing that we are making progress for these veterans who need this help. Every step counts." ‚Äì Shannon Phillips, third-year law student in IU's Maurer School of Law #HoosiersofIU

UPDATE -- Statement from Indiana University President Michael A. McRobbie:

The positive energy and excitement associated with the early weeks of a new academic year on the Indiana University campus in Bloomington has been sadly and abruptly shattered this week, as tragedy struck the campus twice in a very public fashion with the untimely deaths of two promising students.

Yaolin Wang was a junior transfer student who had just begun her IU journey this fall, but who already had immersed herself in the Bloomington campus community, while Joseph Smedley II was a sophomore biochemistry major from Indianapolis who had many friends on campus.

Any time a student dies, the entire campus community is diminished, and to lose two students in a span of days multiplies our collective grief and sense of mourning. To the family and friends of Yaolin and Joseph, I extend our deepest sympathies on behalf of the entire Indiana University family. Our thoughts and prayers are with you in this time of unfathomable sorrow and loss.

To students who feel they need some extra support in dealing with these tragic events, resources are available to help. IU Counseling and Psychological Services has counselors available around-the-clock and I would encourage you to make use of this service by calling (812) 855-5711 and selecting option 1.

There is no way to prepare for the sudden and premature loss of life that has occurred in our community this week. The best we can do, perhaps, is to support one another and make the time to the cherish our friends and loved ones every day.

Again, our heartfelt sympathies go out to the family and friends of Yaolin Wang and Joseph Smedley, both of whom have left us far too early.

A message from Indiana University Bloomington Provost Lauren Robel:

I write to you now about two sad events in the IU Bloomington community‚Äîthe tragic death of Yaolin Wang, a junior from the People's Republic of China, and the disappearance of Joseph Smedley II, a sophomore from Indianapolis, who was reported missing on Monday.

Yaolin had just turned 21 years old. She had only been on the IU Bloomington campus since this fall, having transferred from North Seattle Community College to study at the Kelley School of Business. Our hearts go out to her friends and family at this time, and I hope you will keep them in your thoughts and prayers.

A City of Bloomington Police Department investigation is still underway, but police have confirmed that this was an isolated event that poses no threat to our students.

Indiana University police continue to investigate the disappearance of Joseph Smedley II, 20, whose last known communication was a text message to a family member on Monday. Flyers with Joseph's description and photo (see below) are also being distributed around Bloomington, and anyone with information about his whereabouts is urged to contact IU Police at (812) 855-3499.

All of us who are part of the IU community are deeply troubled and concerned by these recent events. During such difficult moments, it is truly heartening to see the outpouring of care and support from students, faculty and staff and to know that we can find strength in one another.

If any of our students feel overwhelmed with distress or would like help processing these events, students may see a counselor at IU Counseling and Psychological Services on the 4th floor of the IU Health Center. After-hours phone service is also available, free of charge, at (812) 855-5711 (select option 1).

Please be safe and take care of one another.

Lauren Robel, IU Bloomington Provost

status_message:
A message to the Indiana University Bloomington campus community from President McRobbie and Provost Robel:

Hannah Wilson was a beloved daughter, sister, and granddaughter. She was a cherished and treasured friend to her sorority sisters and many others here in Bloomington, at her home in Fishers, and around the country.

Her loss disorders the moral universe and breaks the heart of our community. We join with all of Indiana University in sending our deepest and most profound sympathy to her family. Our thoughts are also with the many IU students, staff, and faculty who loved and taught Hannah, and who join in mourning her.

Hannah was a gifted student, who two weeks from now would have been graduating with a bachelor's degree in psychology, which she hoped to use in service to others. She brought great light to our community, and her strong and continuing impact is clear from the outpouring of grief during the past few days.

Our campus has joined together to honor her memory in gatherings, large and small, since the moment of the tragic news of her death. Our deep bonds as a community are evident in the many ways we have determined to honor Hannah by showing each other strong support and kindness in the wake of this horrible loss.

It is difficult, and perhaps impossible, to understand a loss like this. But we will continue to stand together as a community and support each other during this difficult time.

If you or a friend feels overwhelmed with distress, we urge you to see a counselor during the day at IU Counseling and Psychological Services on the 4th floor of the IU Health Center. After-hours crisis phone service is also available, free of charge, at 812-855-5711 (select option 1).

Michael A. McRobbie, IU President
Lauren Robel, IU Bloomington Provost

Congratulations to the winners of this year's 65th running of the Little 500 bicycle race at Indiana University -- women's champions Kappa Alpha Theta and men's champions Sigma Phi Epsilon!

As part of the men's race on Sunday, riders wore green and purple ribbons in memory of slain IU senior Hannah Wilson. IU Bloomington Provost Lauren Robel asked that a moment of silence be held in her honor prior to the start of the race.

The entire IU community is shocked, devastated and deeply saddened by the tragic and sudden loss of Hannah Wilson. Today, it is difficult to see through the pain and sorrow we all feel. It is never easy to get used to the idea of one of our own, someone so young and loved, being taken from us. Hannah has left us far too soon, and our heart breaks for her, her family and her friends during this extremely trying time.

"Riders! Mount your Schwinn bicycles!" This year's Little 500 kicks off with the women's race today at 4PM EDT, followed by the 65th running of the men's Little 500 race tomorrow at 2PM EDT. Bloomington Campus Alert: Indiana University Police have two suspects in custody as result of an incident on campus early this morning in which one student was injured with a knife. The Bloomington campus was put on alert at approximately 4AM. IU Police arrested the 2 suspected individuals without further incident shortly after 8AM. Both suspects were charged with intimidation and one received an additional charge of battery.

The IU-Notify campus alert system was used throughout the morning to update IU students and employees about the incident. The IU-Notify alert system is only available to students, faculty, and staff at IU campuses. Parents of IU students will only be notified by IU-Notify if a student has entered their parents' home phone, cell phone, or e-mail address as their alternate contact info. More information about IU-Notify, including answers to many common questions, can be found at http://protect.iu.edu/emergency/iunotify

Congratulations to our Indiana Hoosiers high jumper Derek Drouin! Derek has been named the NATIONAL Field Athlete of the Year for the THIRD time in his career! And rightly so. Over the past year, Derek has earned his 5th NCAA high jump championship (the first person to ever do this), his 5th Big Ten Athlete of the Year title, and his 7th Big Ten high jump championship. He's broken the Indiana University school record, the Big Ten conference record, and the Canadian national record in the high jump, in addition to setting a new WORLD record in the heptathlon high jump. And of course he started his year by winning a Bronze Medal in the high jump at the 2012 Olympic Games in London.

It's a safe bet that there's already a spot being reserved with his name on it in the IU Athletics Hall of Fame. We're incredibly proud of all Derek's achievements. Go Hoosiers!

status_message: Happy Birthday to Hoosiers basketball legend Walt Bellamy, 73. Two-time All-American (1960 & 1961), Olympic gold medalist (1960), IU Hall of Fame inductee (1982), Basketball Hall of Fame inductee (1993), the first IU player in history to be taken #1 in the NBA draft, and the first IU player to be named the NBA Rookie of the Year (1962). Campus will be closed Wednesday in observance of the Independence Day holiday. But stop our Lilly Library any other time to examine some of the items in our American history collection. Official statement regarding Lauren Spierer web presence:

"Indiana University Bloomington has not permanently removed the "button" on its home page that directs viewers to resources and information regarding the disappearance of IU student Lauren Spierer. However, after eight months of displaying such information on the campus home page, http://www.iub.edu, the decision was made to rotate the "find Lauren" button with other information on the web site.

For now, the "find Lauren" button will be displayed constantly on the
site the first week of each month. It also will be in a steady rotation of
other news and information items displayed on site. In addition, IU
Communications, which administers the site, has designed two new buttons in the hope that a fresh look will continue to draw attention to this important item.

As it has from the beginning, the entire IU community supports the
Spierer family as it seeks a resolution to this tragic situation and will
continue to help in any way it can. These changes to the IU Bloomington
web site in no way diminish the university's commitment to finding Lauren but rather are an attempt to balance the desire to support the Spierer family with the need to provide a wide range of news and information to all its students and other stakeholders via the campus web site."
